title: For Sale:  Remington 710 Youth .243
postcontent:
The Remington 710 series is a descendant of the popular Remington 700 rifle, and was manufactured by Remington Arms from 2001 to 2006 at their Manufacturing plant in Mayfield, KY.[2]
Based on the same principles as the Remington 700 series, the Model 710 uses a centerfire bolt action cartridge, a 3 lug bolt system as opposed to the Remington 700's dual opposed locking lugs, with a 4 round detachable magazine (or a 3 round for the 7 mm Remington Magnum and the .300 Winchester Magnum). All can be equipped with a bipod and sling, and comes equipped with a gray or olive drab rugged all-weather synthetic stock, and a mounted Bushnell Sharpshooter, 3-9 × 40 scope which is bore-sighted from the factory. The Remington 710 is a moderately priced rifle. With the synthetic stock and the already mounted scope, it makes an adequate gun for the novice shooter or hunter.
This particular model has been heavily criticized, however, because many of the internal parts were made out of plastic, therefore bringing about many questions having to do with the durability of the rifle.
The Remington 710 was significantly improved by Remington and renamed the Remington 770. The 710 model is now discontinued.

This was the first rifle I purchased. I am now looking to purchase a different one. It is in GREAT condition!  $350.00 OBO

title: For Sale/Trade:  FAKE ACOG ALERT!!!!! PLEASE READ!!!!!
postcontent:
Here's another fake Trijicon ACOG copy.. See for yourself

http://www.armslist.com/posts/2357641/texas-optics-for-sale-trade--acog-4x-illuminated-crosshair-reticle-w--rmr

Listing title is "FOR SALE/TRADE: ACOG 4X ILLUMINATED CROSSHAIR RETICLE W/ RMR"


I emailed the guy, and told him everything that was obviously fake about it..
He just got pissed off at me, called me a few not very pleasant things, and told me he is keeping the ad up until he sells it to "someone that isn't trying to cheat me"

Y'all, remember... He is the one selling a $40 knockoff ACOG for $1,000
WILL TRADE FOR:

Here's a list of the top 15 things I immediately noticed wrong about his optic...
15 Problems I noticed right away with this ACOG...

1. No bevel around the eyepiece on the rear
2. Painted white letters saying Trijicon instead of raised lettering built into the optical housing. 
3. No different colored o-rings on your turret caps
4. The "wings" to mount the RMR base to the optical housing are shaped wrong, they're supposed to be angled at 45 degrees, not flat 90 degree angles. (For structural support against impact)
5. The housing and the base are the same color. On real ones, the base is typically shiny, while the housing is more of a matte finish. They're supposed to be two different materials
6. That reticle doesn't exist as an option on real ACOG's
7. The screw holes on the base aren't even the same height... He manufacturer can't even drill a straight hole!
8. Turret caps are the wrong shape. No bevel, serrations are too long. No I letting for caps to seal up against the housing.
9. The housing isn't even close to the being right shape.
10. No pin through the front of the fiber optic connecting it to the walls
11. Fiber optic clear piece isn't perfectly clear like it's supposed to be
12. The walls that are supposed to surround the fiber optic housing on top don't cover almost any of if. These walls are to protect the fiber optic from being damaged if dropped. 
13. The RMR mount doesn't have the front "legs" on it
14. Turret caps don't have the steel cables on them to keep them from falling off
15. This might be the most important one... Nowhere in your ad did you specify a model. Anyone who is selling an actual trijicon ACOG will always add the specific model in because they know the best way to sell it is to put that as the title so other people can search the value of it. They also won't sell an ACOG worth $1,900 for $1,000... 

I can point out 10 more things, but y'all get the idea. Don't buy this
Here's some pictures of the real TA31F-RMR to compare for yourself, there's an obvious difference

title: For Sale:  Mosin Nagant Carbine 44 - Type 53 Chinese
postcontent: The Chinese Type 53 Carbine is one of the more interesting of the Model 1944 Carbine clones; however, the Type 53 has never been sought out on a wide scale by Mosin Nagant collectors. The main reason for this folly is the false notion that the Type 53 is of inferior quality when compared to its counterparts. Nothing could be further from the truth, but this very common opinion still seems to dominate collectors circles. The quality in manufacture of the Type 53 is quite high and the Type 53's place in history rivals any of the Model 1944's. In fact the combat use of the Type 53 may well be greater than any of the M44's. This article will be a brief introduction into the history and production of these little known and misunderstood carbines.
